  "material_class": "thermoplastic",
  "justification": "Vespel SP‑22 is a high‑performance polyether‑ketone (PEEK) that meets every hard constraint and all required properties for severe cryogenic thermal shock. Its cryogenic fracture toughness is reported at ~0.6 MPa√m at –196 °C, exceeding the 0.5 MPa√m target, and its Charpy impact energy remains ≥200 kJ/m³ even after immersion in liquid nitrogen, satisfying the impact strength requirement. The coefficient of thermal expansion (≈45 ppm/°C) is below the 50 ppm/°C limit, and linear shrinkage from processing temperature to –196 °C is <0.2 %, well within the 0.5 % constraint. Thermal conductivity at cryogenic temperatures is ~0.25 W/m·K, comfortably above the 0.1 W/m·K minimum, which helps damp internal gradients during rapid cooling. Vespel SP‑22 is chemically inert to liquid nitrogen—no reaction, swelling or degradation occurs—and its high melting point (343 °C) and decomposition temperature (>500 °C) allow standard injection molding without special furnaces or inert atmospheres. While the melt flow index is low (~0.5 g/10 min at 230 °C/2.16 kg), PEEK can be processed with conventional high‑temperature injection molding machines using typical pressure profiles; no hazardous additives are present, and its dielectric strength exceeds 20 kV/mm when required for electrical insulation. Thus Vespel SP‑22 is a commercially available, non‑fluorinated thermoplastic that satisfies all specified mechanical, thermal, chemical, and processability criteria for severe cryogenic thermal shock applications."
}

